data.content:
In xUnit:

- **`[SetUp]`** → constructor
- **`[TearDown]`** → `IDisposable.Dispose()`
- **`[OneTimeSetUp/TearDown]`** → a shared fixture class with `IClassFixture<T>`

```csharp
// Shared fixture handles one-time setup/teardown
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

// Implement IClassFixture<T> and IDisposable
public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    // Constructor replaces [SetUp]
    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture fixture)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    // Dispose replaces [TearDown]
    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

Key differences:
- xUnit creates a **new class instance per test**, so the constructor/Dispose run for each test (same as `[SetUp]`/`[TearDown]`).
- The `DatabaseFixture` is instantiated **once** and shared across all tests in the class.
- If you need to share the fixture across multiple test classes, use `ICollectionFixture<T>` instead.
